Define a addition-preserving bijection `toAffine_addEquiv` with the affine case to prove `Point` is an abelian group.

This is the fourth in a series of four PRs leading to #9405 and is analogous to #9420

ðŸŽ‰ Thanks! I think this and `toAffine_addEquiv` are all I need to complete the reduction to the universal case.

```suggestion
variable (V) in
/-- A nonsingular rational point on `V`. -/
@[ext] structure Point where
```
Please correct references to `W` in the docstrings that should actually be `V`.

I'm actually meaning to ask for suggestions here. I think `V` is a horrible variable for a Weierstrass curve (over a ring), but I cannot think of another alphabet to use. Should I instead use `W'` over a ring and `W` over a field?

`W'` would be fine, ~~or you could introduce `(W : Jacobian R)` globally and `(W : Jacobian F)` only in sections that deal with fields, and it will shadow the global W within the section. However, beware that you might be unable to change explicitness of W within the sections, see [lean4#3227](https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/issues/3227).~~ (given that the lemmas for the ring case and for the field case are interspersed, this probably isn't an option)
I'm aware of that bug. I made the distinction of `V`/`W` precisely for this reason.
for example, in my opinion these can be compressed to three consecutive lines.

Even if we compress a few lemmas into shorter lines, in the long term there will be issues because we still have to add the analogous `map` lemmas after this, and likely many other things in the future. Note that I haven't added any `simps` to any of the lemmas here, so adding those might make it quite a bit longer too.

For now I will add `Jacobian.lean` into the style-exceptions. Once all these are merged I will split it into three files (TBD): API for triples and equations/nonsingularity (`Jacobian/Basic.lean` ~450 lines), group law polynomials and operations (`Jacobian/Operations.lean` ~950 lines), and the actual group law converted from the affine group law (`Jacobian/Group.lean` ~500 lines). The `map` lemmas will reside in whichever file the relevant definitions reside.

Once all that is done, I will mirror everything for affine and projective coordinates. Eventually we'll take all the `*_simp` stuff from all the files and put them into a standalone file in the same directory, so that will also reduce a few lines.

I think `@[simp]` on the same line as def/lemma is even more common than removing blank lines between grouped lemmas. Searching for `@[simp] ` returns 3577 results across mathlib.
But it's certainly good if you can find a natural subdivision to split the file.
This section looks unnecessary
Can't you add the docstring here directly?
You mean the docstring in `add_decl_doc` right after this? It doesn't seem to compile for me.
Maybe indentation problem? I made it work, see commit to be pushed.

Several missed opportunities to use the anonymous dot notation throughout the file ...
```suggestion
    .some <| (nonsingular_of_Z_ne_zero hPz).mp hP else 0
```
(untested)
What!? Thanks - this is very new to me.

How about
```suggestion
  if hP : W.Nonsingular P âˆ§ P z â‰  0 then
    .some <| (nonsingular_of_Z_ne_zero hP.2).mp hP.1 else 0
```
? Or maybe you want `split_ifs` to always give you three cases automatically ...

I think this is a great idea, since one of these is a junk value and I rarely do `split_ifs`.

Originally `toAffine` took in a *proof* `hP : W.Nonsingular P` and returns the element `if hPz : P z = 0 then 0 else .some <| (nonsingular_of_Z_ne_zero hPz).mp hP`. This turned out to be impossible to work with, since `toAffine_of_equiv` would have to take in a `HEq` proof that `hP` and `hQ` are the same, and I got stuck many times... This makes the infoview a lot more friendly too: we'd be seeing `toAffine W P` rather than `toAffine ...`. In a future PR I might decide to do something similar for other definitions that take in proofs e.g. `Affine.Point.some` and give them junk values when needed.

Note that I have a local branch that combines the conditions for `Affine.slope` similar to this, but haven't made a PR.
Since `F` is a field, isn't it more conventional to assume `u â‰  0`?

Definitely, but this is consistent with the rest of the ring lemmas assuming `IsUnit`. I can add a version assuming `u â‰  0` but some of the places where it's used are a bit more annoying to write with `u â‰  0` (e.g. I could be writing a chain of dot notations `.neg`, `.sub`, `.pow`, `.div` instead of `neg_ne_zero`, `sub_ne_zero`, `pow_ne_zero`, `div_ne_zero`).
Okay. Indeed it seems a big change to replace the condition.

```suggestion
private lemma toAffine_add_of_Z_ne_zero {P Q : Fin 3 â†’ F}
    (hP : W.Nonsingular P) (hQ : W.Nonsingular Q) (hPz : P z â‰  0) (hQz : Q z â‰  0)
```

There are a lot of places where I try to squeeze the hypothesis to the previous line whenever possible (not just this private lemma), but I rather not bother with this for now (maybe a future tidying-up PR).

```suggestion
    rintro âŸ¨_âŸ© âŸ¨_âŸ©
```
(untested)

This doesn't quite work because `toAffineLift_add` needs the `Fin 3 -> F` extracted out, but I don't know why I have this in the first place. If I generalise `toAffineLift_add` to take in a `PointClass F` it works!

This syntax is nice and new to me but isn't shorter here.

If this commit looks good let's send the PR to maintainers.
LGTM!
